<script id="inline-script">

// Opens a simple viewer window containing the original <img> HTML
function showImageFromButton(btn) {
  try {
    const html = Base64.decode(btn.getAttribute('data-imghtml'));
    const w = window.open('', '_imgview', 'resizable=yes,width=900,height=700');
    if (!w) return alert('Popup blocked. Please allow popups for this action.');
    const doc = w.document;
    doc.open();
    doc.write(
      '<!doctype html><html><head><meta charset="utf-8">' +
      '<title>Image Viewer</title>' +
      '<style>body{margin:0;padding:0;display:flex;flex-direction:column;height:100vh}' +
      'header{padding:6px 10px;border-bottom:1px solid #ddd;font-family:sans-serif}' +
      'main{flex:1;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;background:#f8f8f8;overflow:auto}' +
      'img{max-width:100%;max-height:100%;height:auto}</style></head><body>' +
      '<header><button onclick="window.close()">Close</button></header>' +
      '<main>' + html + '</main></body></html>'
    );
    doc.close();
  } catch (e) {
    alert('Could not open image: ' + e);
  }
}

function submitTextPopup() {
    const text = document.getElementById('popupTextarea').value;
    closeTextPopup();
    if (textPopupCallback) {
        textPopupCallback(text);
    }
}

function closeTextPopup() {
    document.getElementById('textPopup').style.display = 'none';
}

var Base64 = {

    // private property
    _keyStr : "ABCDEFGHIJKLMNOPQRSTUVWXYZabcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyz0123456789+/=",

    // public method for encoding
    encode : function (input) {
        var output = "";
        var chr1, chr2, chr3, enc1, enc2, enc3, enc4;
        var i = 0;

        input = Base64._utf8_encode(input);

        while (i < input.length) {

            chr1 = input.charCodeAt(i++);
            chr2 = input.charCodeAt(i++);
            chr3 = input.charCodeAt(i++);

            enc1 = chr1 >> 2;
            enc2 = ((chr1 & 3) << 4) | (chr2 >> 4);
            enc3 = ((chr2 & 15) << 2) | (chr3 >> 6);
            enc4 = chr3 & 63;

            if (isNaN(chr2)) {
                enc3 = enc4 = 64;
            } else if (isNaN(chr3)) {
                enc4 = 64;
            }

            output = output +
            this._keyStr.charAt(enc1) + this._keyStr.charAt(enc2) +
            this._keyStr.charAt(enc3) + this._keyStr.charAt(enc4);

        }

        return output;
    },

    // public method for decoding
    decode : function (input) {
        var output = "";
        var chr1, chr2, chr3;
        var enc1, enc2, enc3, enc4;
        var i = 0;

        input = input.replace(/[^A-Za-z0-9\+\/\=]/g, "");

        while (i < input.length) {

            enc1 = this._keyStr.indexOf(input.charAt(i++));
            enc2 = this._keyStr.indexOf(input.charAt(i++));
            enc3 = this._keyStr.indexOf(input.charAt(i++));
            enc4 = this._keyStr.indexOf(input.charAt(i++));

            chr1 = (enc1 << 2) | (enc2 >> 4);
            chr2 = ((enc2 & 15) << 4) | (enc3 >> 2);
            chr3 = ((enc3 & 3) << 6) | enc4;

            output = output + String.fromCharCode(chr1);

            if (enc3 != 64) {
                output = output + String.fromCharCode(chr2);
            }
            if (enc4 != 64) {
                output = output + String.fromCharCode(chr3);
            }

        }

        output = Base64._utf8_decode(output);

        return output;

    },

    // private method for UTF-8 encoding
    _utf8_encode : function (string) {
        string = string.replace(/\r\n/g,"\n");
        var utftext = "";

        for (var n = 0; n < string.length; n++) {

            var c = string.charCodeAt(n);

            if (c < 128) {
                utftext += String.fromCharCode(c);
            }
            else if((c > 127) && (c < 2048)) {
                utftext += String.fromCharCode((c >> 6) | 192);
                utftext += String.fromCharCode((c & 63) | 128);
            }
            else {
                utftext += String.fromCharCode((c >> 12) | 224);
                utftext += String.fromCharCode(((c >> 6) & 63) | 128);
                utftext += String.fromCharCode((c & 63) | 128);
            }

        }

        return utftext;
    },

    // private method for UTF-8 decoding
    _utf8_decode : function (utftext) {
        var string = "";
        var i = 0;
        var c = c1 = c2 = 0;

        while ( i < utftext.length ) {

            c = utftext.charCodeAt(i);

            if (c < 128) {
                string += String.fromCharCode(c);
                i++;
            }
            else if((c > 191) && (c < 224)) {
                c2 = utftext.charCodeAt(i+1);
                string += String.fromCharCode(((c & 31) << 6) | (c2 & 63));
                i += 2;
            }
            else {
                c2 = utftext.charCodeAt(i+1);
                c3 = utftext.charCodeAt(i+2);
                string += String.fromCharCode(((c & 15) << 12) | ((c2 & 63) << 6) | (c3 & 63));
                i += 3;
            }

        }

        return string;
    }

}

function showTextPopup(callback, heading, initialText = '') {
    
    textPopupCallback = callback;
    const popup = document.getElementById('textPopup');
    const textarea = document.getElementById('popupTextarea');
    const textAreaHeading = document.getElementById('popupTextAreaHeading');
    textAreaHeading.innerText = heading;
    textarea.value = initialText;
    popup.style.display = 'block';
    textarea.focus();
}
function showNoteInputPopup() {
    showTextPopup(function(text) {
        var encodedMessage = Base64.encode(text);
        createMessageButton("",encodedMessage);
    }, 'Create Note:');
}

function showNoteEditPopup(event) {
    const initialMsg = Base64.decode(event.target.getAttribute('data-message'));
    showTextPopup(function(text) {
        var encodedMessage = Base64.encode(text);
        event.target.setAttribute('data-message', encodedMessage);
    }, 'Edit Note:', initialMsg);
}

function noteButtonClickHandler(event) {
        event.preventDefault(); // Prevent focus stealing
        showNoteEditPopup(event);
    };
    
function selectText(containerid) {
    if (document.selection) { // IE
        var range = document.body.createTextRange();
        element = document.getElementById(containerid);
        if(element != null)
        {
            range.moveToElementText(element);
            range.select();
            element.scrollIntoView();
            setTimeout(function() {
                    element.scrollIntoView({ behavior: "smooth" });
                }, 1000);
        }
    } else if (window.getSelection) {
        var range = document.createRange();
        element = document.getElementById(containerid);
        if (element != null)
        {
            range.selectNode(element);
            window.getSelection().removeAllRanges();
            window.getSelection().addRange(range);
            element.scrollIntoView();
            setTimeout(function() {
                    element.scrollIntoView({ behavior: "smooth" });
                }, 1000);
            
        }
    }
}

Dingle, <em data-start="74" data-end="101">Science at the Crossroads</em>, “The Case Against Special Relativity”), with the same setup written explicitly in 4-vector/Lorentz-matrix form so you can see exactly where the equations (1)–(4) come from.<br></span>
<h1 data-start="277" data-end="308">1) Dingle’s setup (rephrased)</h1>
<ul data-start="310" data-end="1680"><li data-start="310" data-end="591"><span>Two inertial frames:<br></span>
<ul data-start="335" data-end="591"><li data-start="335" data-end="434"><span><strong data-start="337" data-end="342">K</strong>: unprimed coordinates <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>c</mi><mi>t</mi><mo separator="true">,</mo><mi>x</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow></semantics></math></span></span>, with clocks <strong data-start="389" data-end="394">A</strong> and <strong data-start="399" data-end="404">H</strong> at rest (fixed <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>x</mi><mi>A</mi></msub><mo separator="true">,</mo><msub><mi>x</mi><mi>H</mi></msub></mrow></semantics></math></span></span>).<br></span></li>
<li data-start="437" data-end="591"><span><strong data-start="439" data-end="444">k</strong>: primed coordinates <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>c</mi><msup><mi>t</mi><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msup><mo separator="true">,</mo><msup><mi>x</mi><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msup><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow></semantics></math></span></span>, moving with speed <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>v</mi></mrow></semantics></math></span></span> in <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mo>+</mo><mi>x</mi></mrow></semantics></math></span></span> relative to <strong data-start="525" data-end="530">K</strong>, with clocks <strong data-start="544" data-end="549">B</strong> and <strong data-start="554" data-end="559">N</strong> at rest (fixed <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><msubsup><mi>x</mi><mi>B</mi><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msubsup><mo separator="true">,</mo><msubsup><mi>x</mi><mi>N</mi><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msubsup></mrow></semantics></math></span></span>).<br></span></li></ul></li>
<li data-start="593" data-end="852"><span>Clocks are “regularly running.” A–H are Einstein-synchronized in <strong data-start="660" data-end="665">K</strong> by a light signal (A emits at <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>t</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mrow></semantics></math></span></span>, reflects at H when H reads <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>t</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow></semantics></math></span></span>, returns to A at <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>t</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mrow></semantics></math></span></span> with A set so that <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>t</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><msub><mi>t</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>−</mo><msub><mi>t</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mrow></semantics></math></span></span>). Similarly N–B are Einstein-synchronized in <strong data-start="846" data-end="851">k</strong>.<br></span></li>
<li data-start="854" data-end="1172"><span>Three <strong data-start="862" data-end="880">meeting events</strong> are considered (Dingle labels them <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>E</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mo separator="true">,</mo><msub><mi>E</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo separator="true">,</mo><msub><mi>E</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow></semantics></math></span></span>):<br></span>
<ul data-start="936" data-end="1172"><li data-start="936" data-end="996"><span><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>E</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></mrow></semantics></math></span></span>: A and B are co-located. They read <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>t</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo separator="true">,</mo><mtext> </mtext><msup><mi>t</mi><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow></semantics></math></span></span>.<br></span></li>
<li data-start="999" data-end="1084"><span><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>E</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mrow></semantics></math></span></span>: H and B are co-located later. They read <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>t</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>t</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mrow></semantics></math></span></span> (H) and <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>t</mi><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msup><mo>=</mo><msubsup><mi>t</mi><mn>1</mn><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msubsup></mrow></semantics></math></span></span> (B).<br></span></li>
<li data-start="1087" data-end="1172"><span><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>E</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow></semantics></math></span></span>: A and N are co-located later. They read <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>t</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>t</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow></semantics></math></span></span> (A) and <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>t</mi><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msup><mo>=</mo><msubsup><mi>t</mi><mn>2</mn><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msubsup></mrow></semantics></math></span></span> (N).<br></span></li></ul></li>
<li data-start="1174" data-end="1680"><span>Dingle then applies “Einstein’s theory” to relate <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>t</mi></mrow></semantics></math></span></span> and <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>t</mi><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msup></mrow></semantics></math></span></span> for these meetings and obtains<br></span>
<span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><semantics><mrow><msubsup><mi>t</mi><mn>1</mn><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msubsup><mo>=</mo><mi>a</mi><mtext> </mtext><msub><mi>t</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo separator="true">,</mo><mspace width="2em"></mspace><msub><mi>t</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mi>a</mi><mtext> </mtext><msubsup><mi>t</mi><mn>2</mn><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msubsup><mo separator="true">,</mo><mspace width="2em"></mspace><mi>a</mi><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>−</mo><mfrac><msup><mi>v</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><msup><mi>c</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac></mrow></msqrt><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>γ</mi></mfrac><mo separator="true">,</mo></mrow></semantics></math></span></span></span>
<span>from which he forms two “rate ratios”<br></span>
<span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><semantics><mrow><mfrac><mtext>rate&nbsp;of&nbsp;A</mtext><mtext>rate&nbsp;of&nbsp;B</mtext></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>t</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msubsup><mi>t</mi><mn>1</mn><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msubsup></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>a</mi></mfrac><mo>&gt;</mo><mn>1</mn><mspace width="1em"></mspace><mtext>(from&nbsp;</mtext><msub><mi>E</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mo>→</mo><msub><mi>E</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mtext>)</mtext><mo separator="true">,</mo></mrow></semantics></math></span></span></span>
<span>and<br></span>
<span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><semantics><mrow><mfrac><mtext>rate&nbsp;of&nbsp;A</mtext><mtext>rate&nbsp;of&nbsp;B</mtext></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>t</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msubsup><mi>t</mi><mn>2</mn><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msubsup></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>a</mi><mo>&lt;</mo><mn>1</mn><mspace width="1em"></mspace><mtext>(from&nbsp;</mtext><msub><mi>E</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mo>→</mo><msub><mi>E</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mtext>)</mtext><mo separator="true">,</mo></mrow></semantics></math></span></span></span>
<span>which he presents as contradictory.<br></span></li></ul>
<h1 data-start="1682" data-end="1723">2) Lorentz transformation (matrix form)</h1>
<span>Use <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>β</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>v</mi><mi mathvariant="normal">/</mi><mi>c</mi></mrow></semantics></math></span></span>, <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>γ</mi><mo>=</mo><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>−</mo><msup><mi>β</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><msup><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mrow><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn><mi mathvariant="normal">/</mi><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></semantics></math></span></span>. In 1+1 dimensions,<br></span>
<span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">Λ</mi><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>β</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mo>=</mo><mrow><mo fence="true">(</mo><mtable rowspacing="0.16em" columnalign="center center" columnspacing="1em"><mtr><mtd><mstyle scriptlevel="0" displaystyle="false"><mi>γ</mi></mstyle></mtd><mtd><mstyle scriptlevel="0" displaystyle="false"><mrow><mo>−</mo><mi>β</mi><mi>γ</mi></mrow></mstyle></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mstyle scriptlevel="0" displaystyle="false"><mrow><mo>−</mo><mi>β</mi><mi>γ</mi></mrow></mstyle></mtd><mtd><mstyle scriptlevel="0" displaystyle="false"><mi>γ</mi></mstyle></mtd></mtr></mtable><mo fence="true">)</mo></mrow><mo separator="true">,</mo><mspace width="2em"></mspace><mrow><mo fence="true">(</mo><mtable rowspacing="0.16em" columnalign="center" columnspacing="1em"><mtr><mtd><mstyle scriptlevel="0" displaystyle="false"><mrow><mi>c</mi><msup><mi>t</mi><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msup></mrow></mstyle></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mstyle scriptlevel="0" displaystyle="false"><msup><mi>x</mi><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msup></mstyle></mtd></mtr></mtable><mo fence="true">)</mo></mrow><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant="normal">Λ</mi><mrow><mo fence="true">(</mo><mtable rowspacing="0.16em" columnalign="center" columnspacing="1em"><mtr><mtd><mstyle scriptlevel="0" displaystyle="false"><mrow><mi>c</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow></mstyle></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mstyle scriptlevel="0" displaystyle="false"><mi>x</mi></mstyle></mtd></mtr></mtable><mo fence="true">)</mo></mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">.</mi></mrow></semantics></math></span></span></span>
<span>Worldlines of the four clocks:<br></span>
<ul data-start="2018" data-end="2149"><li data-start="2018" data-end="2049"><span>A: <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>x</mi><mi>A</mi></msub></mrow></semantics></math></span></span> (rest in <strong data-start="2042" data-end="2047">K</strong>).<br></span></li>
<li data-start="2050" data-end="2081"><span>H: <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>x</mi><mi>H</mi></msub></mrow></semantics></math></span></span> (rest in <strong data-start="2074" data-end="2079">K</strong>).<br></span></li>
<li data-start="2082" data-end="2115"><span>B: <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>x</mi><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msup><mo>=</mo><msubsup><mi>x</mi><mi>B</mi><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msubsup></mrow></semantics></math></span></span> (rest in <strong data-start="2108" data-end="2113">k</strong>).<br></span></li>
<li data-start="2116" data-end="2149"><span>N: <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>x</mi><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msup><mo>=</mo><msubsup><mi>x</mi><mi>N</mi><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msubsup></mrow></semantics></math></span></span> (rest in <strong data-start="2142" data-end="2147">k</strong>).<br></span></li></ul>
<span>Meetings are intersections of these worldlines, obtained by solving <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>c</mi><msup><mi>t</mi><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msup><mo separator="true">,</mo><msup><mi>x</mi><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msup><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant="normal">Λ</mi><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>c</mi><mi>t</mi><mo separator="true">,</mo><mi>x</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow></semantics></math></span></span> with the appropriate constants.<br></span>
<h1 data-start="2279" data-end="2325">3) Compute the three events with <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">Λ</mi></mrow></semantics></math></span></span></h1>
<h3 data-start="2327" data-end="2355">Event <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>E</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></mrow></semantics></math></span></span>: A meets B</h3>
<span>Co-location: <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>x</mi><mi>A</mi></msub></mrow></semantics></math></span></span> and <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>x</mi><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msup><mo>=</mo><msubsup><mi>x</mi><mi>B</mi><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msubsup></mrow></semantics></math></span></span> simultaneously at the same spacetime point. Choose the convenient origin so that this happens at <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>t</mi><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>t</mi><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow></semantics></math></span></span> (Dingle’s stipulation).<br></span>
<h3 data-start="2528" data-end="2556">Event <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>E</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mrow></semantics></math></span></span>: H meets B</h3>
<span>Here <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>x</mi><mi>H</mi></msub></mrow></semantics></math></span></span> and <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>x</mi><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msup><mo>=</mo><msubsup><mi>x</mi><mi>B</mi><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msubsup></mrow></semantics></math></span></span>. Let the <strong data-start="2597" data-end="2602">K</strong>-time at the meeting be <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>t</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>t</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mrow></semantics></math></span></span>. Apply <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">Λ</mi></mrow></semantics></math></span></span>:<br></span>
<span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mo fence="true">(</mo><mtable rowspacing="0.16em" columnalign="center" columnspacing="1em"><mtr><mtd><mstyle scriptlevel="0" displaystyle="false"><mrow><mi>c</mi><msubsup><mi>t</mi><mn>1</mn><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msubsup></mrow></mstyle></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mstyle scriptlevel="0" displaystyle="false"><msubsup><mi>x</mi><mi>B</mi><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msubsup></mstyle></mtd></mtr></mtable><mo fence="true">)</mo></mrow><mo>=</mo><mrow><mo fence="true">(</mo><mtable rowspacing="0.16em" columnalign="center center" columnspacing="1em"><mtr><mtd><mstyle scriptlevel="0" displaystyle="false"><mi>γ</mi></mstyle></mtd><mtd><mstyle scriptlevel="0" displaystyle="false"><mrow><mo>−</mo><mi>β</mi><mi>γ</mi></mrow></mstyle></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mstyle scriptlevel="0" displaystyle="false"><mrow><mo>−</mo><mi>β</mi><mi>γ</mi></mrow></mstyle></mtd><mtd><mstyle scriptlevel="0" displaystyle="false"><mi>γ</mi></mstyle></mtd></mtr></mtable><mo fence="true">)</mo></mrow><mrow><mo fence="true">(</mo><mtable rowspacing="0.16em" columnalign="center" columnspacing="1em"><mtr><mtd><mstyle scriptlevel="0" displaystyle="false"><mrow><mi>c</mi><msub><mi>t</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mrow></mstyle></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mstyle scriptlevel="0" displaystyle="false"><msub><mi>x</mi><mi>H</mi></msub></mstyle></mtd></mtr></mtable><mo fence="true">)</mo></mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">.</mi></mrow></semantics></math></span></span></span>
<span>Read off the time component:<br></span>
<span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><semantics><mtable width="100%"><mtr><mtd width="50%"></mtd><mtd><mrow><mi>c</mi><msubsup><mi>t</mi><mn>1</mn><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msubsup><mo>=</mo><mi>γ</mi><mrow><mo fence="true">(</mo><mi>c</mi><msub><mi>t</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>−</mo><mi>β</mi><msub><mi>x</mi><mi>H</mi></msub><mo fence="true">)</mo></mrow><mspace width="1em"></mspace><mo>⇒</mo><mspace width="1em"></mspace><msubsup><mi>t</mi><mn>1</mn><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msubsup><mo>=</mo><mi>γ</mi><mrow><mo fence="true">(</mo><msub><mi>t</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>−</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>v</mi><mtext> </mtext><msub><mi>x</mi><mi>H</mi></msub></mrow><msup><mi>c</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac><mo fence="true">)</mo></mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">.</mi></mrow></mtd><mtd width="50%"></mtd><mtd><mtext>(A)</mtext></mtd></mtr></mtable></semantics></math></span></span></span>
<span>Because B is <em data-start="2992" data-end="3006">at rest in k</em>, its reading at the meeting is precisely <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><msubsup><mi>t</mi><mn>1</mn><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msubsup></mrow></semantics></math></span></span>.<br></span>
<h3 data-start="3059" data-end="3087">Event <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>E</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow></semantics></math></span></span>: A meets N</h3>
<span>Here <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>x</mi><mi>A</mi></msub></mrow></semantics></math></span></span> and <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>x</mi><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msup><mo>=</mo><msubsup><mi>x</mi><mi>N</mi><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msubsup></mrow></semantics></math></span></span>. Let the <strong data-start="3128" data-end="3133">K</strong>-time at the meeting be <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>t</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>t</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow></semantics></math></span></span>. Apply <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">Λ</mi></mrow></semantics></math></span></span>:<br></span>
<span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mo fence="true">(</mo><mtable rowspacing="0.16em" columnalign="center" columnspacing="1em"><mtr><mtd><mstyle scriptlevel="0" displaystyle="false"><mrow><mi>c</mi><msubsup><mi>t</mi><mn>2</mn><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msubsup></mrow></mstyle></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mstyle scriptlevel="0" displaystyle="false"><msubsup><mi>x</mi><mi>N</mi><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msubsup></mstyle></mtd></mtr></mtable><mo fence="true">)</mo></mrow><mo>=</mo><mrow><mo fence="true">(</mo><mtable rowspacing="0.16em" columnalign="center center" columnspacing="1em"><mtr><mtd><mstyle scriptlevel="0" displaystyle="false"><mi>γ</mi></mstyle></mtd><mtd><mstyle scriptlevel="0" displaystyle="false"><mrow><mo>−</mo><mi>β</mi><mi>γ</mi></mrow></mstyle></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mstyle scriptlevel="0" displaystyle="false"><mrow><mo>−</mo><mi>β</mi><mi>γ</mi></mrow></mstyle></mtd><mtd><mstyle scriptlevel="0" displaystyle="false"><mi>γ</mi></mstyle></mtd></mtr></mtable><mo fence="true">)</mo></mrow><mrow><mo fence="true">(</mo><mtable rowspacing="0.16em" columnalign="center" columnspacing="1em"><mtr><mtd><mstyle scriptlevel="0" displaystyle="false"><mrow><mi>c</mi><msub><mi>t</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow></mstyle></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mstyle scriptlevel="0" displaystyle="false"><msub><mi>x</mi><mi>A</mi></msub></mstyle></mtd></mtr></mtable><mo fence="true">)</mo></mrow><mo separator="true">,</mo></mrow></semantics></math></span></span></span>
<span>so<br></span>
<span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><semantics><mtable width="100%"><mtr><mtd width="50%"></mtd><mtd><mrow><msubsup><mi>t</mi><mn>2</mn><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msubsup><mo>=</mo><mi>γ</mi><mrow><mo fence="true">(</mo><msub><mi>t</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>−</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>v</mi><mtext> </mtext><msub><mi>x</mi><mi>A</mi></msub></mrow><msup><mi>c</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac><mo fence="true">)</mo></mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">.</mi></mrow></mtd><mtd width="50%"></mtd><mtd><mtext>(B)</mtext></mtd></mtr></mtable></semantics></math></span></span></span>
<span>Because N is <em data-start="3435" data-end="3449">at rest in k</em>, its reading at the meeting is <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><msubsup><mi>t</mi><mn>2</mn><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msubsup></mrow></semantics></math></span></span>.<br></span>
<h1 data-start="3492" data-end="3559">4) How Dingle’s relations <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><msubsup><mi>t</mi><mn>1</mn><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msubsup><mo>=</mo><mi>a</mi><msub><mi>t</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mrow></semantics></math></span></span> and <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>t</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mi>a</mi><msubsup><mi>t</mi><mn>2</mn><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msubsup></mrow></semantics></math></span></span> arise</h1>
<span>To reach Dingle’s simple proportionalities from (A)–(B) you now introduce <strong data-start="3635" data-end="3664">the synchronization steps</strong>:<br></span>
<ul data-start="3667" data-end="4639"><li data-start="3667" data-end="4427"><span>In <strong data-start="3672" data-end="3677">K</strong>, A and H are Einstein-synchronized (by the light-pulse procedure he describes). That fixes the relationship between <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>x</mi><mi>H</mi></msub><mo>−</mo><msub><mi>x</mi><mi>A</mi></msub></mrow></semantics></math></span></span> and the time labels <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>t</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo separator="true">,</mo><msub><mi>t</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow></semantics></math></span></span> on A/H for the chosen pair of meetings. In particular, using the fact that H’s reading equals A’s reading for pairs of events that are simultaneous in <strong data-start="3989" data-end="3994">K</strong>, one can eliminate the spatial terms so that the primed times at the B/H meeting reduce to a pure dilation:<br></span>
<span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><semantics><mtable width="100%"><mtr><mtd width="50%"></mtd><mtd><mrow><msubsup><mi>t</mi><mn>1</mn><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msubsup><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>t</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mi>γ</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>a</mi><mtext> </mtext><msub><mi>t</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mi mathvariant="normal">.</mi></mrow></mtd><mtd width="50%"></mtd><mtd><mtext>(1)</mtext></mtd></mtr></mtable></semantics></math></span></span></span>
<span>(Intuitively: in <strong data-start="4174" data-end="4179">k</strong>, B’s time between “B at A” and “B at H” is B’s <em data-start="4227" data-end="4235">proper</em> time along its own worldline, which runs slow by <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mn>1</mn><mi mathvariant="normal">/</mi><mi>γ</mi></mrow></semantics></math></span></span> relative to the <strong data-start="4314" data-end="4319">K</strong>-coordinate time between the corresponding endpoints, once the simultaneity choice has fixed the endpoints.)<br></span></li>
<li data-start="4429" data-end="4639"><span>In <strong data-start="4434" data-end="4439">k</strong>, N and B are Einstein-synchronized. Repeating the same argument but now using the <strong data-start="4522" data-end="4527">k</strong> synchronization to eliminate the spatial term in (B) gives<br></span>
<span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><semantics><mtable width="100%"><mtr><mtd width="50%"></mtd><mtd><mrow><msub><mi>t</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msubsup><mi>t</mi><mn>2</mn><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msubsup><mi>γ</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>a</mi><mtext> </mtext><msubsup><mi>t</mi><mn>2</mn><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msubsup><mi mathvariant="normal">.</mi></mrow></mtd><mtd width="50%"></mtd><mtd><mtext>(2)</mtext></mtd></mtr></mtable></semantics></math></span></span></span></li></ul>
<span>These are exactly Dingle’s equations (1)–(2) on your page 3.<br></span>
<h1 data-start="4703" data-end="4756">5) The two “rate ratios” and why they look opposite</h1>
<span>From (1), considering the pair <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><msub><mi>E</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mo separator="true">,</mo><msub><mi>E</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow></semantics></math></span></span>,<br></span>
<span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><semantics><mtable width="100%"><mtr><mtd width="50%"></mtd><mtd><mrow><mfrac><mtext>rate&nbsp;of&nbsp;A</mtext><mtext>rate&nbsp;of&nbsp;B</mtext></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">Δ</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">Δ</mi><msup><mi>t</mi><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msup></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>t</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msubsup><mi>t</mi><mn>1</mn><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msubsup></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>γ</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>a</mi></mfrac><mo>&gt;</mo><mn>1.</mn></mrow></mtd><mtd width="50%"></mtd><mtd><mtext>(3)</mtext></mtd></mtr></mtable></semantics></math></span></span></span>
<span>From (2), considering the different pair <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><msub><mi>E</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mo separator="true">,</mo><msub><mi>E</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow></semantics></math></span></span>,<br></span>
<span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><semantics><mtable width="100%"><mtr><mtd width="50%"></mtd><mtd><mrow><mfrac><mtext>rate&nbsp;of&nbsp;A</mtext><mtext>rate&nbsp;of&nbsp;B</mtext></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>t</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msubsup><mi>t</mi><mn>2</mn><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msubsup></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>γ</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>a</mi><mo>&lt;</mo><mn>1.</mn></mrow></mtd><mtd width="50%"></mtd><mtd><mtext>(4)</mtext></mtd></mtr></mtable></semantics></math></span></span></span>
<span>This reproduces Dingle’s (3)–(4). The algebra is the Lorentz matrix in (A)–(B) plus the respective synchronization conventions applied to <em data-start="5217" data-end="5228">different</em> event pairs.<br></span>
<h1 data-start="5243" data-end="5283">6) What the matrix form makes explicit</h1>
<span>The 2×2 Lorentz map keeps the spatial terms <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mo>∝</mo><mi>x</mi></mrow></semantics></math></span></span> visible:<br></span>
<span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>t</mi><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msup><mo>=</mo><mi>γ</mi><mtext> ⁣</mtext><mrow><mo fence="true">(</mo><mi>t</mi><mo>−</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>v</mi><mi>x</mi></mrow><msup><mi>c</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac><mo fence="true">)</mo></mrow><mo separator="true">,</mo><mspace width="2em"></mspace><mi>t</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>γ</mi><mtext> ⁣</mtext><mrow><mo fence="true">(</mo><msup><mi>t</mi><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msup><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>v</mi><msup><mi>x</mi><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msup></mrow><msup><mi>c</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac><mo fence="true">)</mo></mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">.</mi></mrow></semantics></math></span></span></span>
<ul data-start="5452" data-end="6008"><li data-start="5452" data-end="5671"><span>To convert them into the simple dilations <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>t</mi><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msup><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>t</mi><mi>γ</mi></mfrac></mrow></semantics></math></span></span> or <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>t</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msup><mi>t</mi><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msup><mi>γ</mi></mfrac></mrow></semantics></math></span></span>, you must choose <em data-start="5566" data-end="5594">which frame’s simultaneity</em> (i.e., which pair of endpoints and synchronization) you are holding fixed.<br></span></li>
<li data-start="5672" data-end="6008"><span>Dingle’s two calculations use different simultaneity choices for the two intervals: <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><msub><mi>E</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mo separator="true">,</mo><msub><mi>E</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow></semantics></math></span></span> is tied to <strong data-start="5783" data-end="5788">K</strong>’s synchronization (A–H), while <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><msub><mi>E</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mo separator="true">,</mo><msub><mi>E</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow></semantics></math></span></span> is tied to <strong data-start="5845" data-end="5850">k</strong>’s synchronization (N–B). The matrix derivation shows that switching which frame you use to eliminate the <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>v</mi><mi>x</mi><mi mathvariant="normal">/</mi><msup><mi>c</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow></semantics></math></span></span> term flips which clock appears slower.<br></span></li></ul>
<span>If you like, I can also write the same derivation with explicit coordinates (choose concrete <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>x</mi><mi>A</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow></semantics></math></span></span>, <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>x</mi><mi>H</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mi>L</mi></mrow></semantics></math></span></span>, <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><msubsup><mi>x</mi><mi>B</mi><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msubsup><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow></semantics></math></span></span>, <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><msubsup><mi>x</mi><mi>N</mi><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msubsup><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>L</mi><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msup></mrow></semantics></math></span></span>) and walk through the light-signal synchronization algebra step by step to show how the <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mo>±</mo><mi>v</mi><mi>x</mi><mi mathvariant="normal">/</mi><msup><mi>c</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></semantics></math></span></span> terms cancel under the respective choices.<br></span></div></div></div></div><div class="z-0 flex <h1 data-start="100" data-end="137">Frames, clocks, and the Lorentz map</h1>
<ul data-start="139" data-end="563"><li data-start="139" data-end="295"><span>Frame <strong data-start="147" data-end="152">K</strong> (unprimed): coordinates <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>c</mi><mi>t</mi><mo separator="true">,</mo><mi>x</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow></semantics></math></span></span>.<br data-start="188" data-end="191">
Clocks <strong data-start="200" data-end="205">A</strong> and <strong data-start="210" data-end="215">H</strong> are <em data-start="220" data-end="229">at rest</em> in <strong data-start="233" data-end="238">K</strong> at fixed positions<br></span>
<span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>x</mi><mi>A</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo separator="true">,</mo><mspace width="2em"></mspace><msub><mi>x</mi><mi>H</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mi>L</mi><mtext>&nbsp;</mtext><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mo>&gt;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mi mathvariant="normal">.</mi></mrow></semantics></math></span></span></span></li>
<li data-start="296" data-end="563"><span>Frame <strong data-start="304" data-end="309">k</strong> (primed): coordinates <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>c</mi><msup><mi>t</mi><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msup><mo separator="true">,</mo><msup><mi>x</mi><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msup><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow></semantics></math></span></span>, moving at speed <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>v</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow></semantics></math></span></span> along <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mo>+</mo><mi>x</mi></mrow></semantics></math></span></span> relative to <strong data-start="395" data-end="400">K</strong>.<br data-start="401" data-end="404">
Clocks <strong data-start="413" data-end="418">B</strong> and <strong data-start="423" data-end="428">N</strong> are <em data-start="433" data-end="442">at rest</em> in <strong data-start="446" data-end="451">k</strong> at fixed positions<br></span>
<span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><semantics><mrow><msubsup><mi>x</mi><mi>B</mi><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msubsup><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo separator="true">,</mo><mspace width="2em"></mspace><msubsup><mi>x</mi><mi>N</mi><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msubsup><mo>=</mo><mo>−</mo><msup><mi>L</mi><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msup><mtext>&nbsp;</mtext><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mo>&lt;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mspace width="1em"></mspace><mtext>(chosen&nbsp;negative&nbsp;so&nbsp;A&nbsp;can&nbsp;meet&nbsp;N&nbsp;later).</mtext></mrow></semantics></math></span></span></span></li></ul>
<span>Lorentz transform (1+1D):<br></span>
<span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">Λ</mi><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>β</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mo>=</mo><mrow><mo fence="true">(</mo><mtable rowspacing="0.16em" columnalign="center center" columnspacing="1em"><mtr><mtd><mstyle scriptlevel="0" displaystyle="false"><mi>γ</mi></mstyle></mtd><mtd><mstyle scriptlevel="0" displaystyle="false"><mrow><mo>−</mo><mi>β</mi><mi>γ</mi></mrow></mstyle></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mstyle scriptlevel="0" displaystyle="false"><mrow><mo>−</mo><mi>β</mi><mi>γ</mi></mrow></mstyle></mtd><mtd><mstyle scriptlevel="0" displaystyle="false"><mi>γ</mi></mstyle></mtd></mtr></mtable><mo fence="true">)</mo></mrow><mo separator="true">,</mo><mspace width="1em"></mspace><mrow><mo fence="true">(</mo><mtable rowspacing="0.16em" columnalign="center" columnspacing="1em"><mtr><mtd><mstyle scriptlevel="0" displaystyle="false"><mrow><mi>c</mi><msup><mi>t</mi><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msup></mrow></mstyle></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mstyle scriptlevel="0" displaystyle="false"><msup><mi>x</mi><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msup></mstyle></mtd></mtr></mtable><mo fence="true">)</mo></mrow><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant="normal">Λ</mi><mrow><mo fence="true">(</mo><mtable rowspacing="0.16em" columnalign="center" columnspacing="1em"><mtr><mtd><mstyle scriptlevel="0" displaystyle="false"><mrow><mi>c</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow></mstyle></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mstyle scriptlevel="0" displaystyle="false"><mi>x</mi></mstyle></mtd></mtr></mtable><mo fence="true">)</mo></mrow><mo separator="true">,</mo><mspace width="2em"></mspace><mi>β</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>v</mi><mi>c</mi></mfrac><mo separator="true">,</mo><mtext>&nbsp;</mtext><mi>γ</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msqrt><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>−</mo><msup><mi>β</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></msqrt></mfrac><mi mathvariant="normal">.</mi></mrow></semantics></math></span></span></span>
<span>Time/space components (and the inverse you’ll need):<br></span>
<span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>t</mi><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msup><mo>=</mo><mi>γ</mi><mtext> ⁣</mtext><mrow><mo fence="true">(</mo><mi>t</mi><mo>−</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>v</mi><mi>x</mi></mrow><msup><mi>c</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac><mo fence="true">)</mo></mrow><mo separator="true">,</mo><mspace width="1em"></mspace><msup><mi>x</mi><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msup><mo>=</mo><mi>γ</mi><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>−</mo><mi>v</mi><mi>t</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mo separator="true">;</mo><mspace width="2em"></mspace><mi>t</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>γ</mi><mtext> ⁣</mtext><mrow><mo fence="true">(</mo><msup><mi>t</mi><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msup><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>v</mi><msup><mi>x</mi><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msup></mrow><msup><mi>c</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac><mo fence="true">)</mo></mrow><mo separator="true">,</mo><mspace width="1em"></mspace><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>γ</mi><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><msup><mi>x</mi><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msup><mo>+</mo><mi>v</mi><msup><mi>t</mi><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msup><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mi mathvariant="normal">.</mi></mrow></semantics></math></span></span></span>
<span>We also stipulate an origin event:<br></span>
<span><strong data-start="1079" data-end="1090"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>E</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></mrow></semantics></math></span></span></strong> (A meets B): <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>=</mo><msubsup><mi>x</mi><mi>B</mi><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msubsup></mrow></semantics></math></span></span> at <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>t</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>t</mi><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msup></mrow></semantics></math></span></span>.<br></span>
<hr data-start="1133" data-end="1136">
<h1 data-start="1138" data-end="1164">Event <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>E</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mrow></semantics></math></span></span>: H meets B</h1>
<ul data-start="1166" data-end="1581"><li data-start="1166" data-end="1278"><span>Worldlines:<br></span>
<ul data-start="1182" data-end="1278"><li data-start="1182" data-end="1215"><span><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>H</mi></mrow></semantics></math></span></span>: <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>L</mi></mrow></semantics></math></span></span> (rest in <strong data-start="1208" data-end="1213">K</strong>).<br></span></li>
<li data-start="1218" data-end="1278"><span><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>B</mi></mrow></semantics></math></span></span>: <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>x</mi><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow></semantics></math></span></span> (rest in <strong data-start="1245" data-end="1250">k</strong>). In <strong data-start="1256" data-end="1261">K</strong> that’s <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>v</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow></semantics></math></span></span>.<br></span></li></ul></li>
<li data-start="1280" data-end="1355"><span>Intersection condition in <strong data-start="1308" data-end="1313">K</strong>: <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>v</mi><msub><mi>t</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mi>L</mi><mo>⇒</mo><msub><mi>t</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mstyle displaystyle="true" scriptlevel="0"><mfrac><mi>L</mi><mi>v</mi></mfrac></mstyle></mrow></semantics></math></span></span>.<br></span></li>
<li data-start="1357" data-end="1581"><span>The primed time at that spacetime point <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><msub><mi>t</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo separator="true">,</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>L</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow></semantics></math></span></span>:<br></span>
<span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><semantics><mrow><msubsup><mi>t</mi><mn>1</mn><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msubsup><mo>=</mo><mi>γ</mi><mtext> ⁣</mtext><mrow><mo fence="true">(</mo><msub><mi>t</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>−</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>v</mi><mi>L</mi></mrow><msup><mi>c</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac><mo fence="true">)</mo></mrow><mo>=</mo><mi>γ</mi><mtext> ⁣</mtext><mrow><mo fence="true">(</mo><mfrac><mi>L</mi><mi>v</mi></mfrac><mo>−</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>v</mi><mi>L</mi></mrow><msup><mi>c</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac><mo fence="true">)</mo></mrow><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>L</mi><mrow><mi>γ</mi><mi>v</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>t</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mi>γ</mi></mfrac><mi mathvariant="normal">.</mi></mrow></semantics></math></span></span></span></li></ul>
<span>So<br></span>
<span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><semantics><mtable width="100%"><mtr><mtd width="50%"></mtd><mtd><mrow><msubsup><mi>t</mi><mn>1</mn><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msubsup><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>t</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mi>γ</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>a</mi><mtext> </mtext><msub><mi>t</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo separator="true">,</mo><mspace width="2em"></mspace><mi>a</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>γ</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>−</mo><mfrac><msup><mi>v</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><msup><mi>c</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac></mrow></msqrt><mi mathvariant="normal">.</mi></mrow></mtd><mtd width="50%"></mtd><mtd><mtext>(1)</mtext></mtd></mtr></mtable></semantics></math></span></span></span>
<span>This is exactly Dingle’s first relation.<br></span>
<hr data-start="1727" data-end="1730">
<h1 data-start="1732" data-end="1758">Event <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>E</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow></semantics></math></span></span>: A meets N</h1>
<ul data-start="1760" data-end="2294"><li data-start="1760" data-end="1848"><span>Worldlines:<br></span>
<ul data-start="1776" data-end="1848"><li data-start="1776" data-end="1809"><span><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow></semantics></math></span></span>: <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow></semantics></math></span></span> (rest in <strong data-start="1802" data-end="1807">K</strong>).<br></span></li>
<li data-start="1812" data-end="1848"><span><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>N</mi></mrow></semantics></math></span></span>: <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>x</mi><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msup><mo>=</mo><mo>−</mo><msup><mi>L</mi><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msup></mrow></semantics></math></span></span> (rest in <strong data-start="1841" data-end="1846">k</strong>).<br></span></li></ul></li>
<li data-start="1850" data-end="2061"><span>Use the <strong data-start="1860" data-end="1871">inverse</strong> transform to write N’s worldline in <strong data-start="1908" data-end="1913">K</strong>:<br></span>
<span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>γ</mi><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><msup><mi>x</mi><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msup><mo>+</mo><mi>v</mi><msup><mi>t</mi><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msup><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mo>=</mo><mi>γ</mi><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mo>−</mo><msup><mi>L</mi><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msup><mo>+</mo><mi>v</mi><msup><mi>t</mi><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msup><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mi mathvariant="normal">.</mi></mrow></semantics></math></span></span></span>
<span>Intersection with <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow></semantics></math></span></span> requires <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>⇒</mo><mo>−</mo><msup><mi>L</mi><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msup><mo>+</mo><mi>v</mi><msubsup><mi>t</mi><mn>2</mn><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msubsup><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow></semantics></math></span></span>, so<br></span>
<span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><semantics><mrow><msubsup><mi>t</mi><mn>2</mn><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msubsup><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msup><mi>L</mi><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msup><mi>v</mi></mfrac><mi mathvariant="normal">.</mi></mrow></semantics></math></span></span></span></li>
<li data-start="2063" data-end="2294"><span>The unprimed time at that spacetime point <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><msubsup><mi>t</mi><mn>2</mn><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msubsup><mo separator="true">,</mo><msup><mi>x</mi><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msup><mo>=</mo><mo>−</mo><msup><mi>L</mi><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msup><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow></semantics></math></span></span>:<br></span>
<span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>t</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mi>γ</mi><mtext> ⁣</mtext><mrow><mo fence="true">(</mo><msubsup><mi>t</mi><mn>2</mn><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msubsup><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>v</mi><mtext> </mtext><msup><mi>x</mi><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msup></mrow><msup><mi>c</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac><mo fence="true">)</mo></mrow><mo>=</mo><mi>γ</mi><mtext> ⁣</mtext><mrow><mo fence="true">(</mo><mfrac><msup><mi>L</mi><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msup><mi>v</mi></mfrac><mo>−</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>v</mi><msup><mi>L</mi><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msup></mrow><msup><mi>c</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac><mo fence="true">)</mo></mrow><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msup><mi>L</mi><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msup><mrow><mi>γ</mi><mi>v</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msubsup><mi>t</mi><mn>2</mn><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msubsup><mi>γ</mi></mfrac><mi mathvariant="normal">.</mi></mrow></semantics></math></span></span></span></li></ul>
<span>So<br></span>
<span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><semantics><mtable width="100%"><mtr><mtd width="50%"></mtd><mtd><mrow><msub><mi>t</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msubsup><mi>t</mi><mn>2</mn><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msubsup><mi>γ</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>a</mi><mtext> </mtext><msubsup><mi>t</mi><mn>2</mn><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msubsup><mi mathvariant="normal">.</mi></mrow></mtd><mtd width="50%"></mtd><mtd><mtext>(2)</mtext></mtd></mtr></mtable></semantics></math></span></span></span>
<span>This is Dingle’s second relation.<br></span>
<hr data-start="2382" data-end="2385">
<h1 data-start="2387" data-end="2433">The two “rate ratios” (Dingle’s (3) and (4))</h1>
<span>From <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>E</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mo>→</mo><msub><mi>E</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mrow></semantics></math></span></span>:<br></span>
<span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><semantics><mtable width="100%"><mtr><mtd width="50%"></mtd><mtd><mrow><mfrac><mtext>rate&nbsp;of&nbsp;A</mtext><mtext>rate&nbsp;of&nbsp;B</mtext></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">Δ</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">Δ</mi><msup><mi>t</mi><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msup></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>t</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msubsup><mi>t</mi><mn>1</mn><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msubsup></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>γ</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>a</mi></mfrac><mo>&gt;</mo><mn>1.</mn></mrow></mtd><mtd width="50%"></mtd><mtd><mtext>(3)</mtext></mtd></mtr></mtable></semantics></math></span></span></span>
<span>From <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>E</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mo>→</mo><msub><mi>E</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow></semantics></math></span></span>:<br></span>
<span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><semantics><mtable width="100%"><mtr><mtd width="50%"></mtd><mtd><mrow><mfrac><mtext>rate&nbsp;of&nbsp;A</mtext><mtext>rate&nbsp;of&nbsp;B</mtext></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>t</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msubsup><mi>t</mi><mn>2</mn><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msubsup></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>γ</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>a</mi><mo>&lt;</mo><mn>1.</mn></mrow></mtd><mtd width="50%"></mtd><mtd><mtext>(4)</mtext></mtd></mtr></mtable></semantics></math></span></span></span>
<span>Both follow directly from the matrix transform and the concrete worldline intersections above.<br></span>
<hr data-start="2790" data-end="2793">
<h2 data-start="2795" data-end="2838">What the explicit coordinates make clear</h2>
<ul data-start="2840" data-end="3510"><li data-start="2840" data-end="3152"><span>The “flip” arises because you are comparing <strong data-start="2886" data-end="2915">different pairs of events</strong> anchored to different <em data-start="2938" data-end="2951">rest clocks</em>: <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>E</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mtext> ⁣</mtext><mo>→</mo><mtext> ⁣</mtext><msub><mi>E</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mrow></semantics></math></span></span> rides along B’s worldline (so B’s proper time is the primed interval), while <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>E</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mtext> ⁣</mtext><mo>→</mo><mtext> ⁣</mtext><msub><mi>E</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow></semantics></math></span></span> rides along N’s worldline and meets A (so A’s proper time is the unprimed interval).<br></span></li>
<li data-start="3153" data-end="3510"><span>In matrix form you can see that getting the simple dilations <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>t</mi><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msup><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>t</mi><mi>γ</mi></mfrac></mrow></semantics></math></span></span> or <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>t</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msup><mi>t</mi><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msup><mi>γ</mi></mfrac></mrow></semantics></math></span></span> requires eliminating the relativity-of-simultaneity term <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>v</mi><mi>x</mi><mi mathvariant="normal">/</mi><msup><mi>c</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow></semantics></math></span></span> or <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>v</mi><msup><mi>x</mi><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">′</mo></msup><mi mathvariant="normal">/</mi><msup><mi>c</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow></semantics></math></span></span>; that elimination happens <em data-start="3384" data-end="3451">with respect to the frame in which the meeting partner is at rest</em> in each case, which is why the two ratios are reciprocals.<br></span></li></ul>
<span>If you want, I can also write these three events as 4-vectors and show the proper-time calculation <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">Δ</mi><msup><mi>τ</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant="normal">Δ</mi><msup><mi>t</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>−</mo><mi mathvariant="normal">Δ</mi><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi mathvariant="normal">/</mi><msup><mi>c</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></semantics></math></span></span> to reach the same results via invariant intervals.<br></span></div></div></div></div><div
